Your snippet looks fine.

In case you want only a fixed delay independent of the query response time (i.e, if you want to send the query every x seconds, whatever time it takes for the previous request to complete) you can use `Flux.interval` combined with `takeUntil` or `any` to stop the flux as soon as you receive the right status.

By using interval instead of retry, you lose the ability to &quot;back off&quot;, i.e. increase retry delay on the fly. However, interval will provide you with :

 - a counter, to track the number of trials.
 - the possibility to configure if you want to wait for a query to be completed before sending another (concatMap) or not (flatMap).
 - Not sure, but you might gain performance because, with the interval approach, you don&#39;t need to create and catch exceptions.

Look at the following example : 

```java

// Repeat every 100 ms
int MAX_ATTEMPTS = 10;
Flux.interval(Duration.ofMillis(100))
    .concatMap(count -&gt; fetchStatus
		    .map(status -&gt; new Report(count, status))
    )
    // Take operator add a limit on the total number of requests sent.
    // You can also use a timelapse instead of a maximum number of trials.
	.take(MAX_ATTEMPTS, true)
    // Take until sends all responses downstream until we get a true status,
    // included. You can replace it with `any` if you&#39;re only interested with the
    // successful signal. If using any, you can combine it with `switchIfEmpty`
    // to raise an error if no true status has been received after a given
    // number of trials.
    .takeUntil(pair -&gt; pair.status)
    .timed()
	.subscribe(value -&gt; System.out.println(&quot;Received: &quot;+ value.get() + &quot; after &quot; + value.elapsedSinceSubscription().toMillis() + &quot; ms&quot;));
```

The above example prints: 

```stdout
Received: Report[count=0, status=false] after 157 ms
Received: Report[count=1, status=false] after 254 ms
Received: Report[count=2, status=false] after 352 ms
Received: Report[count=3, status=false] after 452 ms
Received: Report[count=4, status=true] after 552 ms
```

As we see, even if the query takes 50 ms to execute, it is triggered at fixed interval (every 100 milliseconds).

Your problem is your For-Loop. Why?
Because, lets make it simple and go with numbers. lets say your Array contains:
1,2,3,4,etc. Now you are adding 0. You will add 0 in the first spot then you will push the first spot to the second spot. Next you iterate to the second spot. This spot is already the content of firstspot e.g. already is 0, so you already lost your  content 2. Then you push this 0 to the 3rd spot and so on. Thats why you got everywhere the same Entry. 

Try this.
```java
public void insert(String string) {
